commText: B0$ About time I did something in IPL, pleased about it. Was a good team effort, glad the batters played with freedom, good signs to come. We got the players to do it up front, hopefully we can take this result and form in the next game. I have to fit in (playing well against spinners), you have to adapt, can't be one dimensional. The wicket was starting to hold a bit more, and it also spun a bit. Back of a length kept balls skidding on, so we asked our bowlers to drag back the length and make it difficult for their batters. He (Abhishek Sharma) has been bowling well in the nets, asked him to try and spin the ball as much he can.

B0$ We were off a bit with the ball, but I think Mitch Marsh bowled fantastic. He was our best bowler. To come up 9 runs short is disappointing. I don't think the pitch slowed down a lot, they took pace off. When you lose wickets in the middle it can be extremely difficult. He's (Axar) in good touch. For us it was about, we get off to a good start and we know that him and me will have to handle their spinners with the ball spinning back in. Holding Axar can be difficult. We have been losing too many wickets through the middle.

They started the innings by dismissing the dangerous Warner for a duck, but then DC added a 112-run partnership between Mitch Marsh and Phil Salt. The duo looked like they'd take the game away, but shortly after the halfway stage the wickets began to tumble. Neither of the two set batters could continue for much longer after their fifties, and the pitch got slower to make things tough. Puzzling tactics from DC as well who kept holding Axar back to play into SRH's match-ups. A sense of relief for Markram and his boys, who got back to winning ways, with Abhishek Sharma and Klaasen setting up this win with first innings fifties. Over to the presentations now...

B0$ The pitch was similar to the pitch we had during our practise here, it was keeping low and stopping a bit. We didn't want to play anything fancy and played according to the ball. I had a plan with Brian Lara, he told me to go after the fast bowlers. I was going for it against the fast bowlers, and luckily it paid off. All three games here have been won by the chasing team, but the highest score batting first is 172. We are seeing a surface that doesn't have grass, we are seeing a surface that is low scoring. Just got to be positive (in the powerplay),  One day can be your day, the next day maybe not. In the future I will try thinking of going above the top, but I to be honest I won't change much. Need to be positive with the bat, we'd rather get out caught in the deep (near the boundary), rather than getting stumped or struck in the crease lbw. Hopefully can get a big score tonight. Every experience against the new ball is worthwhile, especially against some of the best bowlers, looking forward to tonight. He was a big player for us Washi (Sundar), batting wise and his bowling speaks for himself. I am not sure what the team is, but I'm pretty sure they have made the plans and done it right.

"Good evening from Kotla. Been a hazy, partly cloudy day all along but the cloud cover doesn't look threatening thus far. The teams are beginning their warm-ups as we speak," quips our correspondent B0$ who's present at the Arun Jaitley Stadium.

For the Sunrisers, Harry Brook, barring his century against KKR, has looked completely out of touch. In a tournament like IPL, consistency is the key, so hope Brook realises the same at the earliest. Their other batters haven't been able to chip in with any significant contributions either. Same is the case with Delhi Capitals for whom, captain David Warner, all-rounder Axar Patel and to an extent - Manish Pandey have been their only saving grace. It's a venue that has assisted spinners, so it won't be a surprise if the trend continues. Salt who was promoted to open the innings along with Warner in the previous game got out for a golden duck. Will he get another chance to feature in the playing XI, or will there be some more chopping and changing? All our questions will be answered in a bit, for now stay tuned for the toss and teams..

B0$ Two teams languishing at the bottom of the points table - Delhi Capitals and Sunrisers Hyderabad are set to face-off each other in the 40th clash of Indian Premier League 2023 folks. The last time these two teams locked horns with each other, Delhi Capitals came out on top by 7 runs. The batting of both these teams has been a big disappointment this season, no wonder why they are struggling to get any winning momentum behind them and making it to the playoffs from this situation looks nothing more than a distant dream for both of them.

B0$ by B1$ 
 
At the halfway mark in their campaigns, both Delhi Capitals and Sunrisers Hyderabad are looking for that second wind as they begin the unforgiving second half of the season with their reverse meet-up at Delhi's Feroz Shah Kotla ground. On form and at their home ground, the Capitals do look like the team that enjoys the upper hand going into Saturday's (April 29) double-header but there's not a lot separating the two sides in IPL 2023. Besides NRR of course, which means despite only two wins and four points each, SRH are placed slightly better off at the ninth spot in the standings as opposed to their bottom-placed hosts. 
 
The Capitals picked up a second successive win against the same rivals, in Hyderabad last week, by defending what seemed a sub-par 144/9 halfway into the game courtesy the spin choke, that's been their strength, and a fine captaincy display from David Warner. For SRH in that game the only bright spot was Washington Sundar's return to form with the ball in hand, but they've since lost the services of the India all-rounder due to a season-ending hamstring injury. 
 
At the core of their struggles, for both the teams, has been that missing spark in batting. DC have managed to snap their five-match losing streak they started the season with, with two wins on the bounce now but Warner has been over-burdened at the top of the order and the only one consistently among runs (which probably somewhat justifies his middling strike-rate this year). The support at the other end has been constantly missing. With Prithvi Shaw not firing, Mitch Marsh only just about beginning to show glimpses of his batting prowess and Rishabh Pant unavailable, DC have been guilty of frequent chopping and changing in search of an ideal combination. Shaw has just got the axe and could likely stay out for foreseeable future, or so hinted head coach Ricky Ponting. 
 
 
SRH, too, have deviated from their first-choice opening combination, and have struggled thus far to pin down that best XI. In order to shield Harry Brook from the unfavourable match-up against spinners, the Englishman has now been promoted to the opener's role which has resulted in both Mayank Agarwal and Abhishek Sharma being shunted up and down giving their batting order a very unsettled look. Barring Brook's century, their batting displays have lacked the firepower. It's been a start-stop first-half for SRH, losing and winning two each of the first-four before going on another (ongoing) losing streak of three that they'll be desperate to break away from before being relegated to the elimination race instead.

Both the Australians addressed the group, which Ponting had earlier said would be about trying to address why the good work in the nets is not really translating into success on the field. Otherwise, the hosts are unlikely to make any tweaks to their winning combination. Mukesh Yadav proved an excellent Impact Sub and would likely be reprising the role. 
 
B7$ Kotla is another ground David Warner absolutely loves, having scored 885 runs here, including seven fifties and a hundred, in 31 outings. At no. 5, the DC captain is the only batter from the side among the top-15 batters. But his season strike-rate of just 119.53 would be a cause of concern for the side.

When he arrived this year, he was with the NCA for a few weeks, working really hard on his fitness and was in good physical shape.
